0.body: With sharec you can share and management configuration across projects, keep your code up to date and start new projects in one command.
0.title: Introduction

1.body:
Create configuration project and init npm inside. Install sharec as dependency: npm i --save sharec Add postinstall script to root package.json file: "scripts": { "postinstall": "sharec"
} Create configs directory. Place some configuration files to the created configs directory. Create package.json file inside configs directory and add required dependencies for tool what you need. Publish configuration with npm publish command or just push it to git repository. Install it wherever you want with npm install command. If you want read more detailed manual â€“ look at official demo config and check sharec package if you looking for API reference.
1.title: Quick start

11.body:
mkdir my-awesome-configs
cd my-awesome-configs
npm init -y

2.title: Example

3.body: Sharec allows you install configuration via CLI with short and friendly commands. Use it in your configuration packages.
3.title: Overview

4.body: At this moment, sharec supports: npmignore eslint eslintignore babel yaspeller browserslist postcss gitignore husky jest lint-staged stylelint commitlint prettier Other .json or .yaml files will be merged by keys. Files with different extension will be just copied.
4.title: Supported configs

5.body: Versionable configuration packages (try out demo config ) Create boilerplates, like create-react-app (see dead simple example here )
5.title: Potential use-cases

6.body: If you want to include these files, you should name them without dot - gitignore, npmignore. It needs, because originally named files would not be readed during installation.
6.title: .gitignore and .npmignore

7.title: Options

8.body:
If you want to force upcoming sharec configs â€“ just add ignore flat to your projects's sharec field: { "sharec": { "ignore": true }
}
8.title: Ignoring configuration

9.body:
If you see some unexpected behavior and want to help with solution - you can provide some debug information about with DEBUG environment variable. It allows to see everything what happens inside of sharec flow. { "scripts": { "postinstall": "DEBUG=true sharec" }
}
